How the Financial Rules of Football Will Affect Neymar’s Transfer to Paris
The rules limiting the financing of European football clubs will not interfere with Neymar’s record transfer from Spain’s Barcelona to Paris-Saint Germain, France.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the power to ban teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
The financial fair play (FFP) rules introduced by UEFA in 2011 state that PSG will have to demonstrate that Neymar's transfer was not financed without major losses.
Barcelona paid EUR 222 million to buy Neymar out of his contract, and Neymar will demand a salary of several tens of millions a year.
There are several financial conditions following Neymar's transfer to France.
Since the PSG team is funded by a rich Cathar family that has become rich in energy sales, it can afford to bring Neymar into an already star football family.
Clubs can spend huge sums on buying players, but on the other hand they have to prove legal sources of income, allowing them to cover the overheads of football-related business activities.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after his appointment as UEFA Director in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that were in debt in search of new reinforcements were ultimately defrauding and risking bankruptcy if banks or owners refused to secure them.
In 2011, FFP’s rules redirected their attention from club debts to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model that Roman Abramovich used with Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with potential and spent a lot of money on players y to build a global brand - was suddenly not so advantageous.
In the current three-year trial period ending in 2018, clubs may report a loss of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite the fact that Platini had to leave his post in 2015, his successor, Aleksander Cheferin, is determined to defend the ban on excessive spending.
"The FFP rules still apply and we are committed to strengthening them in the future," Andrea Traverso said last week for the Associated Press, which oversees compliance with FFP rules.
Although PSG has paid the amount for the purchase of Neymara in a one-off payment, it may distribute the amount for accounting purposes to the full duration of the contract.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, so the transfer can be broken down to EUR 44,4 million each year for five years.
The first wave of the highest sanctions FFP hit in 2014 PSG together with Manchester City, owned by Abu Dhabi Group.
The PSG suffered a fine of EUR 60 million ($82 million) - which was later reduced to EUR 20 million - and a command to reduce the Champions League team to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is careful about teams that can try to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their income through companies associated with club owners.
Thus, even if the Cathar company sponsors the PSG once the financing exceeds the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the billing of the amount.
A similar measure was taken by UEFA in 2014 after it decided that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority of the PSG team was too high.
According to some reports, part of Neymar's income in the PSG could be reimbursed by the MS Football Organising Commission 2022 in Qatar.
However, PSG and MS 2022 representatives in Qatar denied that Neymat should become an ambassador to the World Cup in football and that such a maneuver would easily be revealed by UEFA officials.
The previous sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will closely monitor any attempt to circumvent the rules,
According to Tuesday's informed UEFA, there was no investigation into Neymara's transfer to the PSG.
The source of this report wished to remain anonymous as it was not entitled to comment on the PSG situation, said The Associated Press.
The last published financial statements show that PSG closed 2015-2016 with a net profit of EUR 10 million and a turnover of EUR 542.4 million.
The accounts for the current financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expects the arrival of Neymar to be a huge opportunity for sponsors, merchandising and selling jerseys.
The club promises to increase its turnover by up to 30 percent from signing the contract.
Spain’s league leaders, obviously concerned about the departure of one of the biggest stars, sought to thwart Neymar’s departure, arguing that PSG would violate FFP’s rules.
“This is a clear case of “financial doping” of the club and the state,” said the President of la Liga Javier Teba for the Spanish newspaper AS, referring to the ownership of PSG by the Cathar Syndicate.
Arsenal Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by the American sports tycoon, shares the same position of the La League on the financing of the club.
"It is the result of ownership that has fundamentally changed the football world over the past 15 years," Wenger said on Thursday.
