NHS prescribes controversial HIV treatment to 10,000 patients
Patients have been given access to ‘transformative’ treatment for HIV prevention since September on the basis of the Supreme Court’s decision to fund NHS.
The English National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) pill, which is used before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period through the health service.
NSH agreed to finance the trial period after the Court of Appeal supported the Supreme Court’s decision last year, stating that NHS had funds to pay for PREP despite a statement that the drug should be financed by local authorities.
The decision announced on Thursday was taken by NHS England by Director General Simon Stevens as a ‘significant intervention’, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a ‘deciding moment’.
The sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start receiving patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018 will be fully implemented across England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of transmission of HIV between patients at risk.
Pre-sex administration means that there are enough specific medicines in the patient’ s body to prevent infection.
These medicines can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Tested patients include homosexual or bisexual men, transsexual people, and HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
The clinics shall identify eligible participants who will sign their consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transsexual people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GP in the UK can also register at their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program comes to taxpayers at £10 million and NHS England has signed a contract to distribute drugs this week after obtaining an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to collect clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: ‘This important intervention should be complemented and fully utilised by the ever-expanding and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than 30 years' effort to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, executive director of NAT (National Aids Trust), said: ‘We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and patients at risk, it will offer the possibility of changing the English HIV epidemic.
Since September, NSH has been offering patients who are at high risk of HIV infection a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and is not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will lead to improvements in the quality of many lives.
We accept this statement with pleasure.'
Ian Green, Managing Director of Terrence Higgins Trust, said: ‘Priority number one must be the rapid deployment of tests throughout the country; we must make it available to each patient.
We now have a PrEP test drug and we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.'
Shadow Health Secretary Sharon Hodgson said: ‘The beginning of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delay and delay by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Follow-up tests will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PREP.
It is now important that we start the tests as soon as possible throughout the country to protect those who are exposed to HIV and together end the spread of HIV in society.'
