A Becoming Resemblance: The artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the center of one of the rooms in the New York Fridman Gallery there are several faces of different skin shades - white, black and brown - hanging from the ceiling on the wires. Each one of them seemed to fall out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral and hair swabs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized disclosure of secret cable on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which started on August 2nd, bears the name A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, which combines her experience with technology, IT and art, and Manning's - transsexual and pioneering dissident, whose sentence reduced Obama three days before he left the post of President of the United States.
By algorithmic analysis of Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a razor-sharp, if not intellectual comment about the yield of DNA, as well as many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken since she was young about being considered a woman. She was convicted in 2013 on the basis of 20 charges, including violations of six spy laws, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photographs were held by prison employees, and only one black and white photograph of lower quality, which Manning, visibly concerned with, is sitting in the driver's seat in a platinum blonde wig she is now associated with.
In 2015, there were still positive responses to the 2012 Dewey-Hagborg project Stranger Visions.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create a picture of possible forms of these people.
And that's when she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were preparing an interview with Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to complete the article with a portrait," Dewey-Hagborg explained on the occasion of the opening of a new exhibition.
However, visitors and photography were not allowed, so they asked Chelsea if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends within two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Supressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, who presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
Indeed, several days after the comic book was released, President Obama applied for the release of Manning, which was a welcome change after several unbearable years in a military prison in Kansas.
It is interesting, indeed, that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging a war with people who seek to publish government information and transgender troops while trying to find new ways to incite hatred in areas he should support with his tweets.
In response to a question regarding this particular timing Dewey-Hagborg stated that "everything is happening for a reason".
Under the statement of the artist on one of the walls of the gallery, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter "i" in the surname is filled with heart) after the end of "self-involved factionism, which is based on gender, race, sexuality and culture".
On the opposite side are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - centipede letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By classifying 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to a sophisticated scientific dictionary of artist) Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"I hope that people will get away with it, that our genome does not matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it their own way," said Dewey-Hagborg.
"DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them."
The last specimen of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is the only page from the graphic novel mentioned above.
It depicts Manning as she emerges into King Kong's style from United States Disiplinary Baracks Prison with a megaphone in her hand.
"Once they stop you from speaking, they will win," it says.
"Never let yourself be silenced."
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," said the Philadelphia artist.
"When I think about it, I get goose bumps."
Manning has not yet visited the exhibition personally - which was foretold in a comic book - but when she does, she will be welcomed in the center of the room with her masks, her own genomic portraits, sorted as a crowd of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the nearly 160 cm tall statue of Maningo, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded in pencil.
"They were placed on walls in the past, but this time I wanted them to feel the crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said about the portraits.
"I wanted to give the impression of mass movement, which takes the form of Chelsea and frees her."
