"In the near future, we will complete the WADA plan" - Vice-President of the Russian Government Mutko
Vice-President of the Russian Government Vitala Mutko said that it would not take long to implement the remaining World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) criteria and the re-establishment of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA).
“A part of the criteria of the new plan has already been completed and RUSADA has already obtained the right to planning and testing in cooperation with the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
In view of this, the WADA plan has been updated," Mutko said on Thursday.
The Vice-President commented on the second part of the WADA plan to comply with the Code - which describes the criteria for the renewal of RUSADA - which was recently published on the organization's website.
According to Mutko, the code contains nothing that should worry Russia.
“Everything has been announced and everything will also be implemented.
The results will be available to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future," he added.
However, one of the above criteria calls for a public announcement of the results of the WADA investigation investigated by Richard McLaren about the alleged government's doping sponsoring of Russian athletes.
On the subject, Mutko said: “We are conducting an investigation, since our anti-doping system has obviously failed.
All measures have been taken.
However, there were no state programs in our country and we cannot confess to something that never existed."
Mutek's words were confirmed by Vitaly Smirnov, Director of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
In an interview with Russian RSport Smirnov, he admitted the problems of Russian anti-doping agents, but he added: “On many occasions we have stated that the report contains controversial attitudes and regulations.
No one plans to accept the report without reservation," Smirnov concluded.
WADA suspected RUSADA of performing doping controls within Russia in November 2015 immediately before the doping scandal.
However, the organisation allowed planning and unification of testing under the supervision of international experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD) this June.
After visiting the Moscow headquarters of the organization in July, the CEO of WADA Olivier Niggli stated that RUSADA was "on the right track" to renew its validity.
