Startups to help your company not become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the level of employee satisfaction of her e-commerce startup, but she didn't find an adequate survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, unprofitable, or even misleading.
And even though she promised the anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their distrust of the process.
"I was looking for consistency and objectivity," said Errett, owner of the hair care company Madison Reed, based in San Francisco, who employs 75 people.
So she asked for outside help.
New startups from the field of human resources are constantly appearing in the market, which help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the particular intention of measuring employees’ duties, startups allow companies to vote quickly, target specific teams and demographic groups, also offers absolute anonymity of employees and hotline for complaint, and in some cases also allow informants to bypass their superiors and contact the director directly.
"There are instruments like Strava and Fitbit on the market that monitor your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of the startup of Glint based in Reedwood City.
Errett said that Glint made her more aware of what her employees were thinking and how they were feeling in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and the votes of specific teams, Glint offers a thermal map of the company and a brief overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of low rating managers - which allows the user to work on the correction.
Companies are beginning to realize that it is necessary to pay attention to the culture of the working environment - in case they become another Uber - which is thrown into scandals after a former employee posted a post on his blog describing the company environment and harassing employees who dare speak openly.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys represents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let's Talk Payments website, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global sector of control, regulation and compliance by 2020 may exceed $18.8 billion.
Startup Convercent from Denver, Colorado, which helps companies to prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before the Uber scandals.
Almost 600 Convercent clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
He recently accepted Uber under his wing.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable flash surveys, collect confidential information in real time and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
Where the Director-General is involved, complaints shall be sent directly to the Management Board.
"The Court of Public Opinion has authorized regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and executive director of the startup Convercent.
If the company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or unethical behavior - and if regulators do not intervene - it can face costly consequences as a result of customer boycott, employee exhaustion or court proceedings, Quinlan added.
Ruby Tuesday’s restaurant network, employing over 25,000 people across 500 locations, uses the Convergence for more than a year to raise employees’ awareness of corporate policies and procedures and ensure easy way to contact corporate management.
Earlier, if the employee wanted to report any problem, he had to trace a phone number or e-mail to the management of the company, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful solution.
Often it was a deterrent and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, the general representative of Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no reliable way to track complaints from employees.
Now that the company is using the Convercent, rapid detection and resolution of problems that have never been reached before by managers, sitting in offices, for miles away from the real solution of complaints - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
"This is coming closer to a holistic, overall view of employees' experience," said Vitrano, who manages Ruby Tuesday's risk management group.
"We also protect shareholders from litigation by employees."
The companies ceased to take the ethics, values and participation of employees lightly in 2002 after Arthur Andersen’s accounting firm collapsed after Enron’s fall on the abuse of employees’ ethical rights, Quinlan said.
But it was only when “social media was shining on the whole thing,” that companies began to realize that in the online world they could not simply hide their skeletons in the closet.
"Before people started using technology to monitor ethics, they relied on faith," Quinlan added.
Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and opportunity approved by courageous capital investors, which supported both start-ups.
As part of his February campaign, Convercent raised $10 million in total from companies like Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and eventually took away $47 million in capital.
Glint won $10 million in November from Bessamer Venture Partners and won $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and risk capital.
The increasing number of researches clearly confirms that today’s employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets, such as Silicon Valley, the main advantage is not high salaries and interesting projects.
Employees want to see that they are accepted and appreciated and that they devote their time to a company that seeks a positive mission.
"If people are happy in their work, they perceive that their voice is heard, and that their work is rewarding, they strive for the success of society," said Nina McQueen, Vice President of Global Benefits and Employee Benefits of LinkedIn, who uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors earn if companies and companies thrive, if their employees are satisfied.
And when there is an analytical tool on the market that ensures employees' commitment and commitment to the company, it is no wonder that there are many investors who will support this effort.
According to experts on working culture, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is pointless unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The fact is that when a company applies for feedback from its employees, there may be major changes.
And if the change does not occur quickly - at worst, at all - it can cause disappointment and lack of interest to employees.
"As soon as you ask for 4,000 opinions, you must be prepared for 4,000 conversations," said Russell Raath, director of consulting at Kotter International, who witnessed many companies that relied too much on the data itself.
“Because as soon as you don’t finish things, the employees start asking themselves, ‘ Did they hear me at all?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, why should I care?'""
Madison Reed, who now regularly conducts a survey among employees each month, is able to solve the problem within one day thanks to Glint, says Errett.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated by slow decision-making and quality of communication, Errett was able to reorganise several teams within the company and start communication training to solve the problem successfully.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important view of its employees and hopes to achieve high employment in the long term in a field known for frequent redundancies.
"If you do not seek to create a transparent working environment, employees will not believe you," Vitrano added.
“And once you start losing your employees, you lose your customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt."
