Create a graphic novel: a story about A Castle in England
The small castle Scotney Castle recently played a major role in the music video of the Squeeze group, and Margaret Thatcher also found her refuge in it during the 1970s and 1980s.
Scotney, however, witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his cozy spot near the Bewl River in Kent, Britain, which inspired the curly Jamie Rhodes of York County - a famous hobby in historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
"The sight of the writing of a man who is 300 years after death fascinates me," Rhodes says with a serious face.
"When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection."
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who lived in the castle Scotney from the Middle Ages to the Eduard period. Each story illustrates a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, it is not the first Rhodes book inspired by archives: it is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection of inspired documents of the British Library - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
“This is his thumbprint!
