If I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm going back in time.
How I love archives!"
For someone who is so fascinated by old papers, support from National Trust and Arts Council England and the possibility of staying in the castle almost as a dream. (To tell you the truth, I have extended my stay a bit.)
Rhodes spent time exploring Victorian “new” castle, browsing archives and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as hyenas on the wall and bottles that had been dumped in the ditch for centuries.
He walked around the property and examined the ruins of the old castle, talked to gamekeepers, gardeners and sometimes also artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
Last night, he was "drinking whiskey and writing."
Scotney's intimate history is relatively unknown, as National Trust did not gain access to documents until 2006 after the death of Elizabeth Hussey's last heir.
When Rhodes arrived at the site ten years later, employees were only beginning to penetrate the archives that Rhodes described in words such as “the aristocratics of many centuries scatter their hands with the words, ‘Bring it into the attic’.
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps of property: "You may think the land dispute is boring," Rhodes said, "but I came across one case where two families were fighting over birch.
Stop it, guys!"
Some stories in the book use the castle as a stepping stone and sink deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English uprising in 1381.
"I found a record of a riot in the castle from 1380, which was called Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex in the book," Rhodes said.
“The English uprising actually started in this area and I thought that rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they're connected in the end."
Other stories are closely linked to the history of the castle - such as The Priest, who tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th - century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was discovered only a few years after the coffin was discovered).
Rhodes’ favorite family is Darrell’s: “I was intrigued by the male race — men of that time were always in debt and were spending money on things they couldn’t afford.
Various generations of the Darrell family dealt with this by marrying rich or old wives - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to shake the heads of heirs."
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes is searching for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week gig in the Finnish wilderness, where he drew inspiration for his next book on Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century, which was absorbed by nature.
But it's a special place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
"I said to myself, 'Now get the hell back into real life'."
