The White House prop cost taxpayers thousands of dollars.
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the American manufacturing industry last month came to $24,000 according to the Navy records issued by the TIME Weekly.
The green white helicopter Sikorsky VH-3D, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of the program of 17 July in the White House, which was a show of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials were inspecting a product show from all 50 states.
The Connecticut helicopter was exhibited next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a forklift truck from Mississippi.
The military officer of the White House issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, and requested the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn in the framework of an "exceptional" event, reported the records of Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - the units responsible for the helicopter management.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event," wrote HMX-1 commander in an e-mail to his superior, deputy commander of the Air Force the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 on the occasion of the show, the beginning of which is scheduled for 3 p.m. and will remain in place until the entire place was completely cleared, which was planned between 18:00 and 21:00.
The e-mail also said that if there is a delay on departure from the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for the return flight due to the Working Time Regulation.
The original crew remained on site that evening along with the helicopter and along with them a unit of security personnel.
It was not apparent from the records - which the weekly TIME - that the second crew was finally sent.
Hatch Act prevents civil servants from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible breach of this Regulation.
"We wondered if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was fine," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you've been blocked," wrote the deputy commander.
This show "Made in America" was marked by the White House as an official event, and the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political subtexts.
In his participation in the event, the President advocated a health reform that went through the Senate and talked about trying to keep the government in check.
The use of air transport vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
The presidents use them to travel.
However, their presence, purely for presentation reasons, is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane was driving in the background during his first rally in the Melbourne campaign in Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed by complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
"The White House is pleased with the show 'Made in America', which was presented by the products of all 50 states produced by Americans from American materials," said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington and South Lawn area and practice possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany at the beginning of July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to Made in America was part of the current crew training, said the state official.
On the same day, the helicopter unit flew in the framework of "non-president support missions" for another eleven hours.
The White House said that no more props were paid out of taxpayers' money.
Spokesperson Sikorsky said that the company was not involved in any way in the negotiations for the helicopter issue on South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not retain budget records for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the parade is, according to the Navy, difficult to determine.
According to the Ministry of Defence, the hourly price for the fiscal year 2017, the reimbursement of the DoD’s expenditure for VH-3D amounts to $2,380 per flight hour.
Unit logs indicate a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below that amount.
"It is very misleading to report the costs of taxpayers on the basis of estimates for reimbursement of expenses," Walters said.
‘These estimates shall include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs which are included in the annual costs.’
According to the RAND 2015 study, reimbursement of DoD expenditure does not include personnel costs, but includes fuel costs, maintenance costs and contractual costs.
Back then, White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated the use of a helicopter for show purposes.
"The Idea Show this week is to present products produced in the USA," Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state and that they provide jobs to hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, we pride ourselves on helicopters and other military facilities, the production of which involves countless American citizens.
This fact is to be recalled."
It's not clear if Trump was also on a helicopter during his rounds at South Lawn. The only thing to say for sure is that he was behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back in the White House Trump approached a representative of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said, "I own three of my own."
